AGI - The ink of the typewriter fills the sheets remaining over 20 years in the drawer > of a desk and returns the dry chronicle of a year without freedom: the 'caccia' to Italian, l>'orrore delle Foibe, the wrists torn by the iron wire, the "tortures" by the hands of the "sgherri" of the Ozn>a, the stop on the car
To discover the "Diary of Prison" written by Ermanno Mattioli, master esule, was the nephew, Massimiliano Panizzut, today deputy of the League >. The mother's grandfather, born in Pula, where he taught Italian in elementary school, was captured in 1945 by the partisans of Titus when Istria was abandoned by the Italian military garrisons. "My grandparents - explains the MP at AGI - have never talked to us in the details of their experience of Italian exiles. There was some sort of smell in telling these stories.> We must reflect on the silence, even among the institutions, which has been there for 70 years. Young people need to know what happens also for respect for victims."
<div </div
&nbsp;
Panizzut tells that after the death of the maternal grandparents "we went, 20 years ago, in their house of Gorizia to recover the family items and in a small drawer of the desk> in the guest room we found the diary that then I decided to transcribe in a book>". "There was a real ethnic cleansing. Even my mother who - she explains - was a little girl, was forced to leave Istria and all her school friends to follow her parents in Gorizia where they lived in a attic before finding another home and resume a normal life". The book (not on the market) is now part of the material with which associations propose to "maintain memory alive". Ermanno Mattioli wrote the diary of that year as a prisoner. Like when he was boarded on the motorcycle Lina Campanella, loaded with "250 men and 32 women". The cheeks lined by tears for fear of ending in the seals, then the explosion of the ship's bow due to a mine. "The burst, the scare and the danger - we read in the diary on 21 May 1945 - make lose the head to more than one prisoner who in the hope of putting himself in safety, throws himself at sea while having his hands tied and drowns under our eyes". "It is important also to tell in schools the tragedy of the foibe and the exodus Giuliano Dalmata - is the message of Massimiliano Panizzut - because what happened never again. Enough with regimes and totalitarianisms." On the Day of Remembrance, the Legislator re-launched his first signature to revoke the Italian honour granted in 1969 to Marshal Tito by the then President of the Republic, Giuseppe Saragat. "The text - it explains - is firm in the Constitutional Affairs Committee of the House but it is necessary that the Italian State say that that honor not only goes removed but that it did not deserve it". &nbsp;
